review_blob: Yeah its pretty bad, but this isnt the kind of beer youll expect to pushing the boundaries of taste. Best served ice cold with a plate of wings at the local pub or at a BBQ. Ill grab a six of this if I just want some beer - its not meant to be taken too seriously. I prefer it to Molson Old Style Pilsner, which is also cheap and far worse (IMHO).

Not the most amazing of bitters, to be sure, but still enjoyable. Its for drinking (while looking at the label), not analyzing - you wont be overly impressed but also will have no problem drinking it. Black Sheep has many other finer offerings, but one buys this for the novelty factor, right? I keep an empty around myself...
beer_name: Black Sheep Monty Pythons Holy Grail (Bottle)

review_blob: "Youre Not Worthy" - indeed. Shared a bottle of this with a friend as it was $20 in a pub - the menu tried to mimic the label by saying "you wont be able to afford it!", etc. This is 7.2% but its hard to tell until it hits you. Pours dark brown/amber with a faint but sufficient creamy head. Amazing flavor, a complex beer that I feel Ill find new pieces of the flavor puzzle in for every new bottle. Excellent.

When put on the counter the cashier asked me, "this is beer?". Classy, expensive beer with an amber hue and (I found) a very clean, balanced palate which almost tasted like what I expected it to while being promoted as one of the better Scottish ales. If I was a millionaire id probably drink it all the time...... sigh.

Extremely overrated stout with the yuppie nitro-caps packaged in the tall cans, but on the other hand very reliable when the taps read: "bud light, bud, mgd, guinness" (or something). Frankly a lotta pubs have bad selection and if you just want a half-decent beer and arent there to get hammered, guinness can be a good choice :) Its a good beer to start on and progress from into the better ones, but otherwise nothing to write home about.
Not great but not bad. The kind of beer you drink at a party, or with your friends watching the game. I dont think it tastes bad, but the hand-drawn label has more character than the beer itself.

I have always had respect for Fullers... but London Pride is the only one of their beers I truly love and enjoy. Its smoother than ESB, but at the same time has a lot of character to it (coffee, caramel... even a bit of chocolate)... head is a bit small/medium but I felt it fit the beer well.
